Prolog
„I implore you!“, Eirwen, the queen, begged, „don't send her away! She's still a child!“ The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought, his gaze darkened.
The girl looked very much like her mother. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl was seen as weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had only fathered sons up to this point.
„You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That's your punishment for your failure, Eirwen.“ He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did that.
Frostfell wasn't always a single kingdom. It used to consist of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, in the South a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and it came to an endless war between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They proposed sending their only princess as a queen to the North, where she would give birth to a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
„I implore you, my king, do with me as you will, lock me up, banish me or kill me, but spare my child“, Princess Eirwen pleaded, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with repulsion. Maybe, but only maybe, he would show her mercy. With the woman who had been his wife for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times, and who had given him his sons.
„Alright. The child can stay in the palace“, he said, which was noted by the queen with a sigh. „But“, he added, „you will be executed.“
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. „Yes, my king.“ She bowed.
The Ice King ordered his royal advisor to bring the daughter of the queen to a room that was free of Eirwen. After that, he commanded the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
While the guards escorted her to the execution site, it came to a loud uproar among the citizens as they realized that their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people cried, others screamed and attacked the guards. Others again wondered why this was happening, but everyone was in agreement.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they doing this to her?”
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Brandrichter. The woman, who was still the queen, was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even a criminal. It was the most terrifying thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The citizens of Frostfell refused to believe the king and did not want to accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Don't give up, Kari.” This was the end of the reign of Queen Eirwen.
Deathly silence in the palace
Only a knocking was to be heard from the room located entirely to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by wondered what was inside the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors were circulating among the maids. Apparently, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and waiting to be let out.
Her assumption couldn't have been more wrong, thought Ivory and headed towards the south wing, while the staff wandered about and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was hiding behind the door.
The rumors concerned Ivory, of course, because Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. „Lady Kari, are you in there?“, whispered Ivory in front of the door decorated with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if - unlike the last time - access would actually be granted. I still have blue marks from last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but apologized immediately when she recognized who she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, likely to indicate that she was there. Where else would she be?
„May I enter?“, asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory had entered without asking.
From within, Ivory heard a knocking. That likely meant a „yes“. The cold and the sound made Ivory shudder. It felt strange to hear a sound from a room supposedly empty, although Ivory had been entering it for several years already.
„I'll come in“, said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that Ivory was met with in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. There was paper everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and multiple ice sculptures lay about. There were no windows and little to no light. Additionally, it was colder than in the rest of the palace (which already said a lot). The room looked as though a snowstorm had passed through.
The girl lay rolled up in her bed, wrapped in her bedcover, and was reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
„Which notebook is that?“, asked Ivory and sat down beside Kari on the bed.
